title: _.every() returns true for empty collections.
body:
Seems odd to me that ~~`_.each()`~~ `_.every()` returns `true` when `[]` (or an empty collection) is passed to it. The callback doesn't get called at all either, which caused me some confusion when I was trying to debug it (at first I thought it was because of an issue with my callback).

I would expect in such cases either `false` is returned _or_ maybe a `TypeError`? The [spec appears to be ambiguous](http://es5.github.io/#x15.4.4.16) on return values for ~~`each~~ `every`, but I'd humbly suggest that nothing cannot pass the callback's truthy tests and a more reasonable return value would be `false`.

title: _.before docs are unclear
body:
Here are the current docs for _.before:

``` js
  /**
   * Creates a function that invokes `func`, with the `this` binding and
   * arguments of the created function, until it is called `n` times.
   *
   * @static
   * @memberOf _
   * @category Function
   * @param {number} n The number of times `func` may be called.
   * @param {Function} func The function to restrict.
   * @returns {Function} Returns the new restricted function.
   * @example
   *
   * jQuery('#add').on('click', _.before(5, addContactToList));
   * // => allows adding up to 5 contacts to the list
   */
```

Currently it seems like calling `_.before(5, func)` would allow `func` to be called 5 times but in reality it can only be called 4 times. The example as well as the docs can be updated to make this clearer, although I’m not too sure how to phrase this myself.

Changing _.templateSettings is a problem with dependencies
body:
I just ran into this problem with a package I was writing that used another package I wrote. If a dependency (A) lists lodash as a dependency, and package (B) lists both A and lodash as dependencies, lodash will only be installed once at the B level and A will use that version. Which means, if A changes `_.templateSettings`, and then B requires `lodash` and tries to parse something (expecting the original `templateSettings`), it will get the ones set by A instead.

I can't seem to find anything about this anywhere online which makes me think maybe there's some obvious way around this. But if not, this seems like a major problem.

As a more specific, concrete example:

I wrote a package called "grunt-travis-matrix." It uses lodash templates but sets the interpolate pattern to a mustache style.

I started working on another package called "tinder-cli" (no, it's not related to the dating app), which uses lodash AND grunt-travis-matrix. It uses the default patterns for it's templating, but I keep getting "Unexpected token =" because the interpolate pattern is "{{ }}" and thus "<%= %>" falls through to the evaluate pattern, which then can't parse the "=".

I haven't tried this with underscore, but I'm assuming there's a similar issue there. I realize I can pass these patterns in to the `_.template` call directly, but it would be nice to set them in one place, rather than every time.

There are, undoubtedly, other ways around this as well (like deleting the cache for lodash or adding a postinstall script to "npm install lodash --force"), but they all feel wrong. Any ideas?

title: Method to call function passing it current value
body:
For now if I want to call some function on a currently processing array for example, I need to call `.wrap(func).value()()`:

```
_(arr)
    .map(...)
    ... // some chaining here
    .wrap(func).value()();
```

Its rather ugly and unreadable. It would be nice to have some sort of obvious shortcut:

```
_(arr)
   .map(...)
   ... // some chaining here
   .passTo(func);
```

Or something like this.
The main use case is with `Q.all`:

```
_(arr)
    .map(...) // Create array of promises
    .wrap(Q.all).value()();
```

title: add additional check to see if thisArg is provided without an Accumulator
body:
I ran into this trying to set the `thisArg` while explicitly setting `accumulator`to  be `undefined`.

```
var result = _.reduce([1,2,3], callback, undefined, this)
```

The above results in the the first iteration of the callback to be called with index 0 and the result as undefined, instead of index 1 and `1` as the result value. I just did a strict check for `accumulator === undefined` which makes this change "broader" than my particular edge case, but it could also easily be `arguments.length < 3 || (arguments.length === 4 && accumulator === undefined)` if you want to still allow a specific case where you can intentionally set the accumulator to `undefined`. 

I realize this is sort of a toss up on which edge case makes the most sense, though right before 3.0.0 makes it a good time to alter this if it made sense.

title: _.template doesn't work with numeric tags
body:
I was transitioning some Mustache code over to using Lo-Dash's templating system and found that code with numeric tags didn't work as I (or Mustache) expected:

```
_.templateSettings.interpolate = /{{([\s\S]+?)}}/g;

mustache.render('Hello {{a}}!', { 'a': 'world' }); // Hello world!
mustache.render('Hello {{1}}!', { '1': 'world' }); // Hello world!
mustache.render('Hello {{0}}!', ['world']); // Hello world!

_.template('Hello {{a}}!', { 'a': 'world' }); // Hello world!
_.template('Hello {{1}}!', { '1': 'world' }); // Hello 1!
_.template('Hello {{0}}!', ['world']); // Hello 0!
```

Should I expect this to work?  In my case, the data object is a regex.exec result, and it's convenient to reference the capture groups directly as index tags:

```
var dataRegExp = /name:([^,]*),age:([^,]*)/;
var data = 'name:Bob,age:52';
var result = dataRegExp.exec(data);
mustache.render('Hello {{1}}, your age is {{2}}.', result); // Hello Bob, your age is 52.
_.template     ('Hello {{1}}, your age is {{2}}.', result); // Hello 1, your age is 2.
```

title: Support multiple arguments in memoize
body:
Create a key based on all arguments passed to the memorized function.

Given:

``` javascript
var myJoin = _.memoize(function(x, y) {
    return [x, y];
});
```

Use Before:

``` javascript
myJoin('a', 'b'); // ['a', 'b']
myJoin('a', 'c'); // ['a', 'b']
```

Use After:

``` javascript
myJoin('a', 'b'); // ['a', 'b']
myJoin('a', 'c'); // ['a', 'c']
```

title: _.isEqual doesn't work with chained arrays
body:
```
_({}).isEqual({}); // returns true

_([]).isEqual([]); // returns false instead of true
```

The same with 

```
_.isEqual(_({}), {}); // true

_.isEqual(_([]), []); // false
```

This is because `isEqual` compare types _before_ checking for `__wrapped__` property. 
(Type of `_(...)` is `[object Object]`, while array is `[object Array]`).

title: regexp
.reduce with non-associative function is non-deterministic
body:
This may not be a concern for Lo-Dash, or it may be a well-known issue, but I recently realized that `.reduce` on non-Array objects has somewhat bizarre behavior when used with non-associative functions:

```
var diff = function(a, b) {return b - a;}, 
    obj1 = {a: 1, b: 2, c: 3}, 
    obj2 = {b: 2, a: 1, c: 3};
_.reduce(obj1, diff); //=> 2
_.reduce(obj2, diff); //=> 4
```

The function applied to two objects identical in every property, differing only in the order in which properties are declared, has different results.  (And quite conceivably has different results for the same object in different browsers, since iteration order is not specified.)

I ran across this in a [discussion](https://github.com/CrossEye/ramda/pull/257).  Is this something that should be addressed?

title: Add `pipe` equivalent
body:
Current `compose` function is nice and corresponds to mathematical composition of functions

```
_.compose(a, b, c)
// returns function eq of a(b(c))
```

I do not like using compose because while it is written left to right, the execution happens right to left (or rather inside out).

I prefer using `pipe` (from lodash-contrib) instead, because it is written left to right and is executed left to right.

```
_.pipe(a, b, c)(data)
// same as c(b(a(data)))
```
